          "body": "All six cities of refuge established in chapter 20 appear within the Levitical city list of chapter 21 (Hebron, 21:13; Shechem, 21:21; Golan, 21:27; Kedesh, 21:32; Bezer, 21:36; Ramoth, 21:38). This is architecturally significant. The city of refuge offered protection to the unintentional manslayer until the death of the high priest (Numbers 35:25-28) — a proto-substitutionary provision where the high priest's death secured the fugitive's release. By locating all six asylum cities within the Levitical network, the text fuses two concepts: priestly mediation and mercy for the vulnerable. The place where a person ran from death was also the place staffed by those whose vocation was intercession. The Levitical city map is simultaneously a map of grace."
